text.section:
The Board of Public Works, upon the recommendation of the Secretary, may expend moneys appropriated from the Fund, directly or through loans or grants to local jurisdictions, for the following types of projects on Maryland's ocean beaches:
Bulkhead construction;
Dune restoration or construction;
Beach replenishment; and
Land acquisition necessary to accomplish any of the types of projects in this subsection.

Grants or loans for project construction may not be authorized under this section until the Department and the Board of Public Works approve the following items as submitted by the municipality or county, as appropriate, in which the project is located:
An approved description of the project together with a financing plan;
A guarantee of the portion of costs not provided by State and federal assistance;
An agreement to be responsible for beach cleaning, policing, and lifeguard services on any restored or protected beach;
An agreement to convey at no cost to the State any lands or easements granted to the county or municipality and necessary for beach replenishment or dune restoration or construction purposes; and
Local ordinances and codes relating to building setbacks, piling depths, structural techniques for minimizing wind and storm damage, and building after storm damage.

The financing plan submitted by the municipality and county in which the project is located shall:
Set forth a binding percentage allocation between the municipality and the county of the project costs not provided by State and federal assistance;
Set forth the revenue sources to be relied upon to provide the local costs, which without limitation may include:
As to the county:
The recordation tax authorized by Title 12 of the Tax - Property Article;
The admissions and amusement tax authorized by § 4-102(b) of the Tax - General Article;
The county income tax authorized by § 10-103 of the Tax - General Article;
State-collected, locally-shared taxes or designated portions of the taxes;
Taxes authorized by the Tax - Property Article; and
Revenues raised by establishment of an erosion control district established pursuant to Article 25, §§ 161 and 163A of the Code; and
As to the municipality:
Taxes authorized by the Tax - Property Article;
Fees and charges authorized by Article 23A, § 2(b)(33) of the Code or the municipality's charter; and
The admissions and amusement tax authorized by § 4-102(c) of the Tax - General Article; and
Be accompanied by a guaranty of the municipal and county share of such costs duly ratified by the governing body of each subdivision.
